article.headline: Washington 92, San Diego State 81
article.story: SAN DIEGO (AP) -- The Washington Huskies weren't in the mood for another loss. Bobby Jones scored 19 points to lead four Washington players in double figures in a 92-81 win over San Diego State on Saturday night, the Huskies' first win in nearly a month. Nate Robinson scored 16 points, Tre Simmons added 13 and Will Conroy had 12 for Washington (4-3), whose last win had been on Nov. 29, 104-91 against Eastern Washington. Washington then lost three straight, to Gonzaga and at Wyoming and Houston, all by double digits. This game finished a three-game road trip. "We wanted it desperately, because we lost three in a row," coach Lorenzo Romar said. "When you win three in a row, you don't think you can be beat, and if you lose three in a row, you have doubts when you're going to win your next one." Freshman Brandon Heath scored a game-high 23 for the Aztecs (7-5), who were coming off an 83-71 loss at No. 5 Arizona on Dec. 22. The Huskies "are better than most people thought but as good as we thought they were," Aztecs coach Steve Fisher said. "They were a team living on the edge after three straight losses. They made us look less athletic than I think we are." Washington, which was bigger and quicker than the Aztecs, took a 60-45 lead following a slam dunk by Mike Jensen less than five minutes into the second half. Jensen had six points in the first 4:45 of the second half, before the Aztecs even made a field goal, a 3-pointer by John Sharper that made it 60-48. Fisher said the Huskies' press dictated the pace. "We had a pretty low mark in our basketball IQ tonight," Fisher said. "Our inability to execute when the game plan broke down cost us." Freshman Brandon Heath then scored 10 straight points for the Aztecs to pull SDSU to 64-60 with 10:03 to play. The Aztecs stayed close for the next few minutes, and still trailed by four with 8:11 left, 71-67. That was closest they'd get, though. Conroy made consecutive 3-pointers and Robinson also made a 3 as the Huskies began pulling away. Their biggest lead was 88-72 with 2:39 left. The Huskies said San Diego State was their second-toughest opponent so far, next to Gonzaga. "I had a feeling we were focused and we came out ready to play," Jones said. "This says a lot about our potential, but we need to stay consistent." Washington led 50-43 at halftime after pulling away on a 12-5 run highlighted by 3-pointers by Conroy and Robinson. Aerick Sanders scored 18 for SDSU, Wesley Stokes had 13 and Marcus Slaughter 10. "That's not San Diego State basketball," Sanders said. "Their press dictated our tempo on offense. It had us playing a helter-skelter kind of pace, instead of us getting into our set plays like we are capable of. We played right into their hands playing like that."
